Target-Specific Code GenerationThe compiler determines the correct byte order based on the target build architecture.
Architecture Mapping: For well-known architectures, the order is fixed (e.g., x86 is always little-endian).
Compiler Flags: For bi-endian architectures like ARM, compilers use flags like -mlittle-endian or -mbig-endian to decide which order to use for data storage and instruction generation.
Internal Consistency: The compiler ensures that an operation like a bitwise shift works identically across platforms, even if the underlying physical byte arrangement in memory is different.
Memory Layout vs. RegistersEndianness primarily applies when data is moved between memory (which is byte-addressed) and registers (which treat the data as a single atomic unit).
Big-Endian: The compiler generates instructions to store the Most Significant Byte (MSB) at the lowest memory address.
Little-Endian: The compiler generates instructions to store the Least Significant Byte (LSB) at the lowest memory address

