The compiler computes the effective address during pointer arithmetic by multiplying the integer offset by the sizeof the underlying data type, then adding this result to the base pointer address. 
Internally, this is formulaic: Effective Address= Base Address + Index * sizeof(Type)
Type Scaling: The compiler uses the pointer's type to determine the scaling factor. Incrementing a pointer to int adds sizeof(int) (typically 4 bytes), while char adds sizeof(char) (1 byte)

